commitResults.messageTitle: Implement a skeletal version of Duke that starts by greeting the user, simply echos commands entered by the user, and exits when the user types bye.
Add the ability to store whatever text entered by the user and display them back to the user when requested.
Added a new class called Task. Added the ability to mark tasks as done.
Add support for tracking three types of tasks:
commitResults.messageBody:
1. ToDos: tasks without any date/time attached to it e.g., visit new theme park
2. Deadlines: tasks that need to be done before a specific date/time e.g., submit report by 11/10/2019 5pm
3. Events: tasks that start at a specific time and ends at a specific time e.g., team project meeting on 2/10/2019 2-4pm

commitResults.messageTitle: Updated Event, Todo and Deadline so that the type of "done" task would show up when "list" is called (i.e. [E], [D] or [T])
Use the input/output redirection technique to semi-automate the testing of Duke.

Teach Duke to deal with errors such as incorrect inputs entered by the user. Errors included are Insufficient Argument for Todo, Deadline, Event and Done, as well as Wrong Argument (when an invalid keyword is used).
Add support for deleting tasks from the list. Add Insufficient Argument Exception for "delete"
Save the tasks in the hard disk automatically whenever the task list changes. Load the data from the hard disk when Duke starts up.
Store deadline dates as a java.time.LocalDate in my task objects. Accept dates in a format of yyyy-mm-dd format (e.g., 2019-10-15) and print in a different format of MMM dd yyyy e.g., (Oct 15 2019).

Addthe following classes: Ui: deals with interactions with the user Storage: deals with loading tasks from the file and saving tasks in the file Parser: deals with making sense of the user command TaskList: contains the task list e.g., it has operations to add/delete tasks in the list
Add JavaDoc header comments to the code.
Add JUnit tests to test the behavior of the code.
Tweak the code slightly to comply with the given coding standard in CS2103
Give users a way to find a task by searching for a keyword.
